headline: China’s Moonshot Unveils AI Model Ahead of DeepSeek Release
summary: The latest iteration of Moonshot’s Kimi can process text, images, and videos simultaneously from a single prompt, the company said in a statement on Tuesday, aligning with a trend toward so-called omni models pioneered by industry leaders like OpenAI and Alphabet Inc.’s Google.  Seeking to capitalize on reignited investor appetite for the country’s top-tier model makers, Moonshot last month raised $500 million from investors including Alibaba and IDG Capital at a post-money valuation of $4.3 billion, according to people familiar with the matter.  The three firms are among a handful of front-runners in a hotly contested battle among Chinese large language model makers, which at one point was dubbed the “War of One Hundred Models.”

Corning will supply advanced optical fiber, cable and connectivity products to Meta, ‌while expanding its manufacturing capacity in North Carolina, including at its cable factory in Hickory, where Meta will be the anchor customer. Corning will supply advanced optical fiber, cable and connectivity products to Meta, ‌while expanding its manufacturing capacity in North Carolina, including at its cable factory in Hickory, where Meta will be the anchor customer.  Corning's optical connectivity products are among key components required to support the massive computing and data transmission demands at ⁠data centers.

headline: Big Tech earnings to test AI rally as resurgent Alphabet takes lead
summary:
STORY: Microsoft and Meta will kick off Big Tech earnings this week under pressure to prove their costly bets on AI can power another year of strong growth.

That's as a resurgent Alphabet takes the lead in the high-stakes race.

The companies, along with Amazon, are expected to lift their AI spending this year by 30% to more than $500 billion.

It's an unprecedented outlay that will sharpen investor scrutiny.

Some have expressed doubts over whether Microsoft squandered a first-mover advantage in AI it secured through its OpenAI investment.

Meta too is under pressure to show payoffs from its expensive push into superintelligence.

Both stocks declined more than 6% in the last three months of 2025.

While Amazon saw a small 5% gain after its November deal with OpenAI signaled that the largest cloud-computing provider in the U.S. was no longer behind on AI.

Alphabet shares though surged about 29% in that period.

It followed a strong reception of Google's latest Gemini 3 model.

The company also recently struck a deal to power Apple's revamped Siri.

LSEG data showed that in the October-December quarter, Google Cloud revenue growth likely quickened to 35% from 33.5% in the previous three months.

But doubts linger about the real-world benefits for the businesses adopting the technology.

And feeding into bubble fears that hounded the technology industry for much of last year.

headline: Pinterest cuts up to 15% jobs to prioritize AI push, shares sink
summary: Pinterest will trim less than 15% of its workforce, the social media platform said on Tuesday, as ​it plans to reallocate resources to its artificial intelligence-focused roles and ‌strategy.  Shares of the company, however, tumbled nearly 10% after its AI pitch failed to ignite investor ‌enthusiasm, underscoring heightened competition from TikTok and Meta-owned Facebook and Instagram for ad market share.  "Without clear cost savings or a concrete path to AI-driven revenue growth, these cuts look more defensive than strategic," said Emarketer analyst Jeremy Goldman.
